\pard\ql\f1\fs30\sb180\sa180\cf1\keepn\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw12\brdrcf2\brsp80\b 8  Backward pass and gradient routing\b0\par
\pard\ql\f1\fs25\sb160\sa100\cf1\keepn\b 8.1  One backward signal\b0\par
\pard\ql\f0\fs22\sb0\sa160 The language-model loss produces one gradient with respect to the effective weight matrix. The architecture then divides that signal according to what the base geometry can represent.\par
\pard\sb100\sa170\li180\ri180\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\brdrl\brdrs\brdrw28\brdrcf2\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\brdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\shading100\cbpat3\f0\fs22 \f2\fs19 G_effective = d(loss) / d(effective_weight)\line G_projected = projection of G_effective into the base materialiser span\line G_remainder = G_effective - G_projected\f0\fs22\par
