\pard\ql\f1\fs25\sb160\sa100\cf1\keepn\b 8.3  Orthonormal and future non-orthonormal bases\b0\par
\pard\ql\f0\fs22\sb0\sa160 For current orthonormal CHEBY and intended orthonormal DCT bases, projection uses the same basis matrices and axis order as forward materialisation: analysis by the transposed contractions followed by synthesis through the forward contractions. Uncompressed axes are preserved.\par
\pard\ql\f0\fs22\sb0\sa160 A future non-orthonormal basis may not silently use the orthonormal formula. It must register an exact least-squares projector using its Gram matrix or equivalent operator.\par
\pard\ql\f1\fs25\sb160\sa100\cf1\keepn\b 8.4  Avoiding double application\b0\par
\pard\ql\f0\fs22\sb0\sa160 In the initial full-matrix-hook backend, the hook returns G_projected to existing autograd. Existing autograd then produces and applies the coefficient gradient. An explicitly calculated coefficient_gradient may be used for tests and the later streamed backend, but it must not be applied a second time.\par
\pard\sb110\sa170\li180\ri180\brdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\brdrl\brdrs\brdrw28\brdrcf2\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\brdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf2\shading100\cbpat3\f0\fs22 \b Interpretive rule\b0\line The base gets first access to the effective-weight gradient. The remainder receives only what the base representation rejects.\par
